      "item": {
        "type": "markdown",
        "id": "d08fbcd4ea7288bc",
        "text": "Attempting to make progress in the field of \"image\" was for me at first, i.e. in the late 1970s and early 1980s, a very lonely work; I will return to these beginnings later with some remarks. After I had gained enough certainty, I tried to break out of my isolation by compiling an anthology \"Was ist ein Bild?\" which was finally published by Fink Verlag in Munich in 1994. I had been working on the anthology since the late 1980s, and it was initially planned as a volume in the \"Edition Suhrkamp\" series, where it was to appear as early as 1991. I wanted to show that there is a cryptic debate about images, especially in philosophy, but also in works of modern art, which I hoped to interpret in order to give validity to my own intentions. This debate included positions by Maurice Merleau-Ponty, Hans-Georg Gadamer, Hans Jonas, Bernhard Waldenfels, Michael Polanyi, Max Imdahl, and others.1"
